First thing you want to do is setup a ServiceModule in your object graph. 

You want a singleton for your rest adapter that you can use via constructor injection for the rest of the services. Make sure your BASE URL is a constant declared somewhere so you can vary it for different build types. 

Next, you want to use the aforementioned restAdapter singleton to create the rest of your services. 

Every service should be an easy couple of lines

@Provides
SomethingApiService provideSomethingApiServicer(RestAdapter restAdapter) {
    return restAdapter.create(SomeApiService.class)
}

Each ApiService is endpoint based (“api/user” , “api/stores”, etc). 

Ideally, you will then wrap the service in a manager. The manager allows you to use RxJava to chain calls, and abstract the network layer to a single class where your calls are actually made within the manager. The manager is also a singleton

@Singleton
@Provides
SomethingManager provideSomethingManager(SomethingApiService somethingApiService) {
     return new SomethingManager(somethingApiService);
}

In which case in the manager you actually find your network calls

public void addSomething(Something something, Subscriber subscriber) {
    somethingApiService.addSomething(something)
	.observeOn(Whatever thread you want)
	.subscribe(subscriber);
}

That way, your code base would simply have

somethingManager.addSomething(something);

If you ever want to swap your network layer, or add local persistence, you can do it all in the manager without having to change anything in your code base.

So in the actual codebase I just say


public class SomeFragment extends Fragment {

@Inject 
SomethingApiService somethingApiService;

public void onCreate() {
 //yada yada
       Injector.inject(this);
}

